69
00:06:29,323 --> 00:06:34,824
We're looking at the charter as a whole, not just in pieces.

70
00:06:34,864 --> 00:06:36,504
We're looking at the entire document.

71
00:06:37,845 --> 00:06:46,647
Once we complete our work, we'll submit a final report to the mayor and the city council, and then it's in their hands.

72
00:06:47,227 --> 00:06:47,907
They look at it.

73
00:06:48,007 --> 00:06:51,388
If they approve it, it's submitted to the state legislature.

74
00:06:51,928 --> 00:06:58,209
If the state legislature gives it the green light, then it goes to the residents to be voted on.

75
00:06:58,829 --> 00:07:07,796
So nothing that we propose, nothing that we do can be codified until the voters say so.

76
00:07:07,817 --> 00:07:10,559
So this is really in the hands of the voters.

77
00:07:12,961 --> 00:07:15,002
Okay, Medford's current charter.

78
00:07:15,583 --> 00:07:25,311
So many people who look at Medford's charter or maybe know that it's what we call a plan, what is a plan A charter.

79
00:07:27,498 --> 00:07:28,259
It was adopted in 1986.

80
00:07:29,860 --> 00:07:35,503
Before that, we had a plan E charter, which means we had a city manager as opposed to a mayor.

81
00:07:36,244 --> 00:07:37,885
We moved to a mayor form of government in 1986.

82
00:07:41,768 --> 00:07:46,711
All these plan governments are outlined in Massachusetts general laws.

83
00:07:47,792 --> 00:07:54,076
And only a few communities left in the state are still using a plan form of government.

84
00:07:54,736 --> 00:08:07,343
They're considered to be antiquated at this point and Medford is one of the few that are still using a plan form as opposed to creating a more modern charter like the one that's

85
00:08:08,983 --> 00:08:10,444
on the table that's right here.

86
00:08:10,924 --> 00:08:12,786
You'll be able to take a look at if you like.

87
00:08:13,146 --> 00:08:16,148
And as I said, that's also available on our website.

88
00:08:18,830 --> 00:08:24,013
The other thing that we've learned about Medford's Charter is that it doesn't exist in a single document.

89
00:08:24,113 --> 00:08:27,996
So if anybody, if any of you have tried to learn about Medford's Charter and you

90
00:08:28,756 --> 00:08:35,318
go click on Medford's charter from the city website, you'll see a very short couple pages, very short.

91
00:08:36,518 --> 00:08:39,379
The reason for that is because it is a plan a charter.

92
00:08:39,499 --> 00:08:53,262
So it's described in Massachusetts general laws, and it works in conjunction with other state statutes and special acts, which are laws that were that are specific to Medford.

93
00:08:53,762 --> 00:08:54,983
So in order to really

94
00:08:56,623 --> 00:09:00,244
understand Medford's charter, you have to track down all these different sources.

95
00:09:00,804 --> 00:09:02,164
And that can be difficult.

96
00:09:02,544 --> 00:09:07,606
Some of the statutes and special acts go back decades, if not more.

97
00:09:09,306 --> 00:09:16,768
So that's one of our goals is to create an accessible charter that people can look at that's in one document.

98
00:09:17,908 --> 00:09:25,290
So for instance, if you want to know, if you look at the charter on our website, it doesn't say anything about how the school committee operates.

99
00:09:25,990 --> 00:09:36,498
In order to find that, you have to go to Mass General Laws about school committees, and then you have to find whatever special acts passed that apply to Medford in that regard.

100
00:09:36,518 --> 00:09:50,588
A new charter, comprehensive, would supersede all that, and it would exist in one document so that any resident could look at it and understand how the city government works.

